    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\nYou're helping a streamer set up alerts for new followers. Right now, the code sends the same message for everyone, but the streamer wants each follower's username to show up in the alert.\r\n\r\n1. Look at the function `new_follower_alert()`. Right now, it always shows the same name in the message.\r\n\r\n2. Add a **parameter** to the function so it can greet any follower by name.\r\n\r\n3. Update the print statement to include the follower's name.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nA **parameter** is a placeholder in the function definition. When you call the function, you pass in an argument that fills that placeholder.\r\n\r\nTo include a variable like a name in your message, you can combine strings using the `+` operator. Here's an example:\r\n\r\n```\r\nprint(\"Hi, \" + name + \"!\")\r\n```\r\n\r\nMake sure to include spaces **inside the quotes**, like `\"Hi, \"` and `\"!\"`, or the message will get squished together.",
